I think your `Class` definition is fine, the `CodingKeys` enum is not needed but it is okay to leave it like that.

To keep simple you can declare a variable inside `ViewController` of type `[Class]`, this array will hold that data fetched from your url. When you decode this data you save it to that variable, for instance you could do something like: `self?.myData = try! decoder.decode([Class].self, from: data)`.

The myData variable is declare like this:

    fileprivate var myData = [Class]() {
      didSet {
        // All UI related stuff must run on the main thread
        DispatchQueue.main.async {
          self?.table.reloadData()
        }
      }
    }
Using `didSet` property observer is a simple way to reload the data once the variable is updated.

For the table&#39;s data source you should implement a couple of methods. First the one that simple returns the number of rows in section with just a line of code:

    return myData.count
And the method that implements `cellForRowAt` which dequeues a cell and set the information on the appropriate cells&#39; fields. The data to be displayed is in `myData` array, you can use the `indexPath` to subscript the array, like this:

    let dataRow = myData[indexPath.row]
You can look at a very simple project that implements all this at [Github][1]. The project&#39;s single view looks like this:

